{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17592932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17592932"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:20:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:20:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15287"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15287"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.11,0.67,0,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7978"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63633"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7978"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15287"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49080"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19409"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19411"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20861"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63633"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHydatid disease used to be relatively common in Australia, particularly in the sheep farming areas of the country. Now with better hygiene and de-worming of the primary host (dogs), the disease is infrequently seen. When detected, it is usually as a cyst found incidentally on imaging (Image 1).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHydatid cysts are fluid-filled sacs that can form in various organs, most commonly the liver, due to parasitic infection (Image 2). These cysts can cause symptoms depending on their size and location.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the cause of hydatid cysts?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Histoplasma","Cryptococcus","Echinococcus","Cytomegalovirus","Aspergillus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHydatid cysts are caused by infection with the tapeworm \u003Cem\u003EEchinococcus\u003C/em\u003E. The most common species responsible for this condition are \u003Cem\u003EEchinococcus granulosus\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EEchinococcus multilocularis\u003C/em\u003E. These parasites form cysts primarily in the liver, but they can also affect other organs, where the diagnosis will be made on the characteristic ring of calcification around the cyst (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHistoplasma\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003ECryptococcus\u003C/strong\u003E are fungi that can cause infections but do not lead to hydatid cysts. \u003Cstrong\u003ECytomegalovirus\u003C/strong\u003E is a virus that can cause various infections, particularly in immunocompromised individuals, but it does not cause hydatid cysts. \u003Cstrong\u003EAspergillus\u003C/strong\u003E is another type of fungus that can cause lung infections, especially in individuals with weakened immune systems, but it is not associated with hydatid cysts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hydatid cysts are caused by the parasitic infection with the tapeworm Echinococcus.","Echinococcus granulosus and Echinococcus multilocularis are the species responsible for hydatid disease."],"references":["Torbenson M, Washington K. Pathology of liver disease: advances in the last 50 years. Hum Pathol. 2020 Jan;95:78-98. doi: 10.1016/j.humpath.2019.08.023. Epub 2019 Sep 4. PMID: 31493428.","Chan WK, Chuah KH, Rajaram RB, Lim LL, Ratnasingam J, Vethakkan SR. Metabolic Dysfunction-Associated Steatotic Liver Disease (MASLD): A State-of-the-Art Review. J Obes Metab Syndr. 2023 Sep 30;32(3):197-213. doi: 10.7570/jomes23052. Epub 2023 Sep 13. PMID: 37700494; PMCID: PMC10583766","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49080"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15287"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21209"},{"type":"media","id":"21210"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21211"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21209"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/32h8i2zCAgsL8g7vcFc7ckRzGqG6gS.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/32h8i2zCAgsL8g7vcFc7ckRzGqG6gS.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":497,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"21210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21210"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hnFppIlM0l3tfo1Yt536BUef7BJe83.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hnFppIlM0l3tfo1Yt536BUef7BJe83.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":598,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"21211","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21211"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ypvnsSdzmkb4rhZO2mtCL6TimDY4MD.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ypvnsSdzmkb4rhZO2mtCL6TimDY4MD.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":536,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49080"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-21T20: